    "explanation": "<p>The equation is $\\sin ^{-1} x+\\sin ^{-1}(1-x)=\\cos ^{-1} x$. The domain for $x$ where all terms are defined is $[0,1]$. Using the identity $\\cos ^{-1} x=\\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\sin ^{-1} x$, the equation becomes:</p>\n<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\sin ^{-1} x+\\sin ^{-1}(1-x) & =\\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\sin ^{-1} x \\\\ 2 \\sin ^{-1} x+\\sin ^{-1}(1-x) & =\\frac{\\pi}{2} \\end{aligned} $$</p>\n<p>Test for solution within $[0,1]$</p>\n<p>If $x=0 ; 2 \\sin ^{-1}(0)+\\sin ^{-1}(1)=0+\\frac{\\pi}{2}=\\frac{\\pi}{2}$.</p>\n<p>So, $x=0$ is a solution.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>$$ \\begin{aligned}If\\,\\, x & =1 / 2,2 \\sin ^{-1}(1 / 2)+\\sin ^{-1}(1 / 2) \\\\ & =2\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\right)+\\frac{\\pi}{6}=\\frac{\\pi}{3}+\\frac{\\pi}{6}=\\frac{\\pi}{2} \\end{aligned} $$</p>\n<p>So, $x=1 / 2$ is a solution.</p>\n<p>Consider the function</p>\n<p>$$ F(x)=2 \\sin ^{-1} x+\\sin ^{-1}(1-x)-\\frac{\\pi}{2} $$</p>\n<p>Its derivative $F^{\\prime}(x)=\\frac{2}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}}-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2 x-x^2}}$.</p>\n<p>Setting $F^{\\prime}(x)=0$ leads to $3 x^2-8 x+1=0$, which has solutions $x=\\frac{4 \\pm \\sqrt{13}}{3}$. Only $\\frac{4-\\sqrt{13}}{3}$ is in $(0,1)$.</p>\n<p>Since, there is only one critical point, and we found two distinct solutions, these are the only solutions.</p>",
